{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601122"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:13:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:13:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15648"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15648"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.15,0.12,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8339"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71026"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8339"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15648"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56497"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7010"},{"type":"tags","id":"8130"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20115"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71026"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECongenital adrenal hyperplasia represents a group of inherited disorders affecting steroid hormone synthesis in the adrenal glands. The condition results in abnormal production of several key hormones.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes congenital adrenal hyperplasia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["21-hydroxylase deficiency accounts for 90% of cases","Androgen production is consistently decreased","Aldosterone synthesis is typically increased","17-hydroxyprogesterone levels remain normal","11-beta-hydroxylase deficiency is the predominant form"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECongenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH) is an inherited group of disorders affecting steroid hormone synthesis. \u003Cstrong\u003E21-hydroxylase deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is indeed the most common form, accounting for approximately 90% of all cases. The condition results in cortisol deficiency and androgen excess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAndrogen production is consistently decreased\u003C/strong\u003E - CAH actually leads to increased androgen production due to accumulation of steroid precursors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAldosterone synthesis is typically increased\u003C/strong\u003E - Aldosterone levels are typically decreased in salt-wasting forms of CAH\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E17-hydroxyprogesterone levels remain normal\u003C/strong\u003E - Elevated 17-hydroxyprogesterone is the hallmark finding used for diagnosis of classical CAH\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E11-beta-hydroxylase deficiency is the predominant form\u003C/strong\u003E - This form accounts for only about 5% of cases\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe enzyme deficiency leads to reduced cortisol production, which causes increased ACTH secretion and subsequent adrenal hyperplasia. The accumulated precursors are shunted into the androgen synthesis pathway.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Congenital adrenal hyperplasia is caused by enzyme deficiencies in steroid hormone synthesis, most commonly 21-hydroxylase deficiency","The hallmark finding in classical congenital adrenal hyperplasia is elevated 17-hydroxyprogesterone","Enzyme deficiencies lead to cortisol deficiency and androgen excess"],"references":["Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA","Lotfi CFP, Kremer JL, Dos Santos Passaia B, Cavalcante IP. The human adrenal cortex: growth control and disorders. Clinics (Sao Paulo). 2018 Sep 6;73(suppl 1):e473s. doi: 10.6061/clinics/2018/e473s. PMID: 30208164; PMCID: PMC6113920"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56497"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15648"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56497"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T19:02:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T19:03:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8339"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71026"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"